{"questionId":"13919703","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The assumption that the value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi></math> is constant is not correct. It can be shown that</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">Hence, the new model is given by</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>98</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>14</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>41</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mi>s</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:left;\">When <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, it is known that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the upper bound for the velocity according to this model, given that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>40</mn><mo> </mo><mn>000</mn></math>.&nbsp;Give your answer to four significant figures.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>upper limit occurs when&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>40000</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The <em><strong>M1</strong> </em>can be implied by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40000</mn></math> substituted into their part (c)(i).</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>349</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><msup><mi>ms</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<strong><em>A1</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Answer must be to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math> sf.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"13919703","referenceCode":"23N.3.AHL.TZ0.1civ","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the upper bound for the velocity according to this model, given that 0<s≤40 000. Give your answer to four significant figures.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"iv","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.11—Indefinite integration, reverse chain, by substitution","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.14—Setting up a DE, solve by separating variables","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.6—Modelling skills"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":3}
